---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ConceptPageHero from '../../components/concepts/ConceptPageHero.astro';
import ConceptPager from '../../components/concepts/ConceptPager.astro';
import { getConcept } from '../../lib/concepts';

const c = getConcept('rotation');
---

<Layout title={`${c.title} | Identity Engineering`}>
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<ConceptPageHero
			scene={c.scene}
			tag={`${c.tag} · ${c.layerLabel}`}
			title={c.title}
			lede={c.blurb}
			scrollHint={c.scrollHint}
		/>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Definition</div>
				<h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-white md:text-4xl">
					Stability through spin — and the tension it creates.
				</h2>
				<p>
					<strong class="text-white/80">Rotation</strong> is the gyroscopic stabilization of the Identity Stem. Like a spinning top or a planet on its axis, coherent angular momentum keeps the stem oriented and resistant to small disturbances. High coherent spin reduces wobble. Weak or incoherent rotation leads to precession and vulnerability under load.
				</p>
				<p>
					However, Rotation has a double relationship to tension: it both <strong class="text-white/80">stabilizes existing tension</strong> and <strong class="text-white/80">generates new tension</strong>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02] px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<div class="mb-6 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Mechanics</div>
				<ul class="space-y-6 text-lg text-white/55">
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Axis:</strong> the Identity Stem (Time layer). Rotation does not create the axis; it stabilizes its orientation.
					</li>
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Spin:</strong> coherent, repeated motion around the axis (practices, rhythms, ritualized commitments that reinforce stem coherence).
					</li>
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Tangential force:</strong> habits and Owned Acts that feed substance into the system without creating lateral thrash or fragmentation.
					</li>
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Wobble:</strong> a quality metric for how much the stem precesses or loses orientation under internal or external load.
					</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<div class="mb-6 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Rotation and Tension</div>
				<p class="text-lg text-white/55 mb-6">
					Rotation interacts with inner tension in two opposing ways:
				</p>
				<ul class="space-y-5 text-lg text-white/55">
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Stabilizing effect:</strong> Strong, coherent rotation increases resistance to disturbances (gyroscopic effect). This allows an identity to hold significantly more internal tension — conflicting demands, emotional load, external pressure — without losing its fundamental orientation or coherence.
					</li>
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Tension-generating effect:</strong> Rotation simultaneously produces its own centrifugal tension — a drive toward expansion, differentiation, and in extreme cases fragmentation. This self-generated tension acts like a Fliehkraft: it pushes parts of the identity outward and creates new internal stress that must be absorbed.
					</li>
				</ul>
				<p class="mt-6 text-lg text-white/55">
					For rotation to remain stabilizing rather than fragmenting, sufficient <strong class="text-white/80">Mass</strong> and internal cohesion are required. Without enough Mass, high rotational speed shifts from protective to destabilizing.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02] px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<div class="mb-6 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Engineering work</div>
				<p class="text-lg text-white/55">
					Increase coherent spin while ensuring that the centrifugal tension it generates can be productively absorbed. Rotation is not an end in itself — it is a tool to make higher levels of productive tension sustainable.
				</p>
				<div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-black/30 p-6">
					<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[3px] text-white/40 mb-3">Practice loop</div>
					<ul class="space-y-3 text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
						<li>Identify one practice that genuinely increases stem coherence (raises spin quality).</li>
						<li>Identify one activity that adds lateral thrash or centrifugal overload without enough Mass to absorb it.</li>
						<li>Observe over 2–3 weeks: Does increasing coherent rotation allow you to hold more meaningful tension without fragmentation?</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<ConceptPager id="rotation" />
	</main>
</Layout>
